Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**App.xaml.cs** â€” override `CreateWindow` and hook `Stopped`/`Resumed`/`Destroying`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**NoteViewModel.cs**:

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---------|----------|
| Save on background | `window.Stopped` fires when fully hidden |
| Restore on resume | `window.Resumed` fires when returning from background |
| Android back button | Also save in `Destroying` (skips `Stopped`) |
| Keep it fast | `Preferences` is synchronous and lightweight â€” avoids ANR/watchdog kills |
| First launch | `Resumed` doesn't fire initially, so load the saved value in the ViewModel constructor |

**Pitfall to avoid:** Don't save in `Deactivated` â€” that fires just from pulling down the notification shade or showing a dialog, not actual backgrounding.
